<p>The most significant uniting factor behind UKIP&#8217;s appeal, which finds common cause among its disparate supporters is immigration, and in particular, the scale of immigration. Antipathy to that is the galvanising force drawing significant new support from many on the left as well as right. The mainstream parties have immigration policies, which a sizeable minority of the electorate vigorously oppose, or regard as inadequate. Until the Conservative party, in particular, is seen to address the issue more effectively (and fairly), UKIP will remain a thorn in their side, potentially depriving them of power after 2015. At present, a weak and divided Labour leadership is failing to capitalise on Conservative divisions. By 2015, that may change.</p>
