    <li class="comment even depth-5" id="dsq-comment-279151">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-279151" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-279151">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-279151">Footguards</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-279151" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-279151" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I first heard your arguments in the 1980s from an ex-Maoist<br />
lecturer who was by then a libertarian outrider. I thought his ideas absurd and nothing since has convinced me otherwise. </p>
<p>You class political beliefs in terms of methods and not<br />
values. You also assume that there is a shared code of values between all left wingers (and indeed all right wingers too). Politics is far more nuanced. There<br />
is a spectrum of opinion on both the left and right. Finally you make the mistake of saying that political beliefs have remained unchanged since the 18th century. Adam Smith was a liberal in his time and was strongly criticised by Edmund Burke, the founder of modern conservatism. Who was right wing, Smith or Burke? </p>
<p>Taking your yardstick of placing a politician who increases<br />
the power of the state on the left then Churchill must be left wing. He was an advocate of rail and mine nationalisation in the 1920s, accepted mos
8000
t of Attlee’s reforms when he returned as PM, and significantly increased the power<br />
of government over trade as a Liberal minister before WWI.</p>
<p>What about Gordon Brown? He unwillingly bailed out the bank, but so did Bush, was he a socialist? Brown, as chancellor and prime minister, encouraged private sector involvement in state affairs: privatising the Tote, PFIs,<br />
Public-Private Partnership for the London Underground, private companies employed by the National Health, and the start of Academies. Was he right wing?</p>
<p>No one craved the destruction of government more than Marx, who said under communist the state would<br />
‘wither away’. Was he right wing?</p>
<p>To recap: Churchill and Hitler on the left, Brown and Marx<br />
on the right. Now do you see why I think this argument is absurd?</p>
<p>Also, who are true right wingers? Burkeans (who were/ are skeptical about an untrammelled free-market) or Neo-liberals like you. It is arrogant to say only your part of the spectrum are ‘true right.’ Look at the debate over<br />
selling forests or loosening green belt controls. Right wingers were on both sides of the debate. (We’re back to Burke v Smith here.)</p>
<p>And yes many on the extreme right are racist. Look at<br />
European politics today.</p>
</div>
