            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-217551" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-217551" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Those who base their assessment of a party on what it stands for rather than the comments some of its supporters post in reaction to a newspaper article hidden behind a paywall have considerably more authenticity behind their own ventured opinions. As you state the comments merely confirmed what you had assumed, I must conclude you had made your decision without devoting much effort to what UKIP, as a party, addresses with policy. </p>
<p>I have voted for UKIP twice because I have done what you have not. I recognised the utter contempt in which I, as an ordinary constituent, am held by the major parties, exemplified by the ratification of a very important EU treaty which I know few bothered to read. That is just one example, but there is a much more recent one, same sex marriage. If you ignore the issue it addresses, the important aspect of this is the manner in which it was very carefully introduced as legislation so the public could play no part in it. If this was for introducing the death penalty, would this process be acceptable?  I certainly hope not.</p>
<p>The people of Scotland have openly displayed their rejection of the established parties by voting SNP, despite there being no discernible increase in support for independence. English voters have had little option other than the established parties and voting has decreased as a consequence. UKIP&#8217;s appeal to those who haven&#8217;t voted for anyone should tell you it is not extremists it appeals to, it is the disenfranchised. That includes many who have voted for a party to oppose another, rather than in support of anything it represents and now they no longer have to, as they will recognise the possibility their vote for another party really will count for once. They can vote for something for a change.</p>
<p>There is some pride in this article that says in too many words &#8220;I told you so&#8221;, but all it really says is you are lacking in objectivity. The party you represented no longer represents its own members, never mind being genuinely interested in the electorate, and the electorate have an opportunity to advise you and them that that is not acceptable. That is not extremism, that is democracy. How sad you cannot recognise this.</p>
