<p>But extremism is in the eye of the beholder. Anyone threatened will call his or her threatener &#8216;extremist&#8217;.</p>
<p>You appear to argue that UKIP, by uniting things such as political correctness, the EU, curtailments on free speech etc, rather than approaching them one by one that you have uncovered evidence of lack of moderation.</p>
<p>What form of evidence is that?</p>
<p>You will remember how Mrs Thatcher saw union power. She looked at high taxes. She observed inflation which is a tax on savers. She looked for a common theme. She identified that theme as being state control and a lack of liberty.</p>
<p>That is what every political philosophy does: it looks for links. To approach a series of problems as if each is unconnected is the mark of an uneducated fool &#8211; which you certainly are not.</p>
<p>Why then, must UKIP be denigrated for also seeking such links when such an exercise is the only way to tackle problems which are rarely independent of each other?</p>
<p>You are an honourable man &#8211; but I believe you assign faults to UKIP which are just not there.</p>
