        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-218981" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-218981" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Most certainly grass roots political movements/parties may appear &#8220;extremists&#8221; just because all vibrancy is gone out of &#8220;official&#8221; parties once they all agree on certain managerial assumptions and the conflict is taken out the current political thinking. If memory serves me right, the conflict or disagreement is at the very root of politics as such. Political landscape has been dominated by &#8220;we-all-singing-from-the-same-hymn-sheet&#8221; approach, which is contrary to real political struggles, so UKIP is a good reminder of what&#8217;s politics is all about. One more interesting thing that parties that propose to stand for &#8220;national interest&#8221; spring around Europe and seem to be champions of &#8220;nation state&#8221; or at least take a stand against some visible or perceived encroachment on the territory of the nation-state. So, it&#8217;s back to basics , namely the issue of sovereignty.</p>
