    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219131">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219131" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219131">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219131">E Hart</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219131" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219131" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I think you totally miss the point. UKIP is a response to the failure of the electoral system and the three main parties. You simply cannot have an effective political system if it is set with an in-built bias. It is rather like expecting a bowl to run straight. It isn&#8217;t going to happen. The result is obvious &#8211; disaffection. Democracy cannot and shouldn&#8217;t function with one flavour and governments that consistently put a minority interest above the majority. It&#8217;s a thesis without an antithesis. As for synthesis, you know how to whistle don&#8217;t you? </p>
<p>This is where UKIP comes into it own. UKIP looks to Europe for its scapegoat &#8211; and heavens, there is enough wrong there to make it a likely culprit &#8211; but the real fault lies closer to home. It lies in democracy/representation deficit disorder. The government doesn&#8217;t seem to realise it is supposed to be for the people, by the people&#8230; If it isn&#8217;t that &#8211; and there is prime facie evidence that it isn&#8217;t &#8211; then you have to ask for whom it exists. Enter: UKIP. Sights set, it continues to blast off at Europe, when the skulking, shifty, Golem is staring them in the face and claiming expenses on houses it doesn&#8217;t live in and on moats around those that it does. Westminster is a cosy, corrupt, fief; a place of patronage and rotten boroughism, where often the last consideration is for those who voted.</p>
<p>UKIP&#8217;s sound and fury is a lot of contrived nonsense shooting off at the wrong targets but it does have a political role to play. It shows up the whole unrepresentative, unresponsive charade for what it really is &#8211; a dire con on the British public.</p>
<p>National sovereignty with or without Europe is leeching away. If it wasn&#8217;t because of successive governments agreeing reciprocal arrangements with the EU, it would because of trans-national corporations frightening Britannia into believing she didn&#8217;t need knickers and that she could rely on them to choose her wardrobe.</p>
<p>&#8220;The first is that bugbear I identified in my email to Ronald: all or any of the words ‘liberal’, ‘metropolitan’, and ‘elite’. This idea that there is a conspiracy of the privileged to cheat and oppress the masses, forcing them beneath a yoke in which alien agencies are involved, leaps from any study not only of Marxism but (on the right) of Poujadism and Peronism.&#8221; </p>
<p>Let me ask you something, where do you think the present political trajectory leads? Does it lead to a more equal or inclusive society or does it take us in the opposite direction? British politics only ever plays with half the deck. Surely, having served in it, you must know that by now?</p>
<p>It is a case of aphids, ants and superants and about as interesting. The real question is, when can the electorate expect to get a fully functioning, representative democracy in Britain? We&#8217;ve had the Stefordian charade, how about something real that appeals to the majority?</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="dsq-comment-219811">
