    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219141">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219141" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219141">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219141">Jon</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219141" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219141" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>And this opinion coming from a Party that judges its own membership as &#8220;mad, swivel eyed loons&#8221;&#8230; no wonder the Conservative hierarchy is out of touch with public sentiment. Why does having considered opinions make you extremist? The trouble is though, the Government doesn&#8217;t really seem as if it wants its citizens to have views on anything at all. UKIP challenges make it less possible to cover-up. So they label those who speak out about key subjects and policy implementation as in need of psychiatric help. It&#8217;s up to the Government and opposition parties to convince the electorate that the their ideology is better than UKIP&#8217;s, not criticise those who threaten to expose the EU for what it really is. Despite his intelligence, our Prime Minister can&#8217;t seem to put a better argument forward though and that is clearly worrying many who expect senior politicians to stick their neck out and show leadership in difficult times. UKIP&#8217;s popularity is not not about a single issue as Matthew Parris claims, because &#8211; as we have witnessed in recent years &#8211; Britain, fuelled by inaction is becoming a haven for the worst kinds of human nature, economic failure, political corruption and extremism. The EU and Government merely endorses this by doing nothing and effectively telling us all to shut up and live with it. At least UKIP recognises that there is a problem to deal with in the first instance.</p>
</div>
        </div>

