            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219341" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Matthew, I&#8217;m sorry I agree with most of your posts and enjoy reading your work, but on this I disagree with you.  I honestly believe that the current state of Britain cannot be solved and recitified by the current batch of politicians.  I have come to believe that there is now in most Western &#8220;Democracies&#8221; a ruling class, which encompasses all the major parties and is fundementally opposed to personal freedom.  You see it in the plethora of laws governing interpersonal relationships, you see it when people not smiling enough at olympic events are arrested, you see it when people are imprisoned for expressing racist views on Twitter but others are given probation for repeated burglary.  In the current model we are suffering from the tyranny of the agressive minority.  If enough activists can get enough column inches, they can make almost anything illegal (or legal).  You get the Prime Minister Of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland commenting on a footballer biting another footballer when he is on an important trade mission, you get homosexual marriage as a priority even though in all probability less than 1% of the population is gay and not all of them want it.  I would support UKIP if I still lived in the UK, even though I think Nigel Farage is the acceptable face of some pretty extreme people, mainly because I loathe the shiney faced PR buffoon who is &#8220;leading&#8221; Britain now, along with all of his chums.  Add to that the thought of supporting a party thet stubbornly refuses to slaughter Ed Balls is not acceptable.</p>
