            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219751" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219751" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Matthew, I think you fundamentally misunderstand what is going on in the country. Your old party is becoming obsolete and has no answers for any section of the peoples&#8217; of Britain.</p>
<p>The UK Independence party is not an extremist party at all, but I imagine your faith in the direction of travel the Tories have taken of late blinds you to observing these wider events in the country.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219771">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219771" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219771">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219771">country_exile</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219771" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219771" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>As a UKIP supporter (and former Conservative up until recently) I don&#8217;t think there is a &#8216;conspiracy&#8217; by the liberal left and/or the European Union.</p>
<p>I just think the British people have been badly let down by politicians of all parties who increasingly hold them and their &#8216;unfashionable&#8217; views on education, patriotism, benefit reform, the EU and immigration in contempt. Anyone who reads Mr Parris in the Times (and his excellent book Chance Witness) will know he largely took this view of the electorate himself when he was an MP. I remember him saying &#8216;some of the electorate are pretty contemptible&#8217;. At least he had the guts to say what many of the political class actually think &#8211; and to be fair he generally puts his money where his mouth is.</p>
<p>However, the Conservative Party is slowly dying &#8211; like all the mainstream political parties. The tectonic plates are shifting both in England with UKIP and through the SNP in Scotland. I am not naive enough to believe UKIP has all the answers but at least they are asking the questions that others will not.</p>
<p>The SNP was dismissed as an irrelevance as recently as the late 90s. Now they run Scotland and are dictating the terms of the Scottish independence debate. UKIP will have the same impact in England although it will be an evolution not a revolution. It&#8217;s time and high time the political establishment and commentariat woke up to the fact their world is changing. Just as we took so long to work out so had ours.</p>
</div>
        </div>

