            <cite id="dsq-cite-219831">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219831">Jonathan foreman</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219831" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219831" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>What a shamefully lazy and dishonest article. How can you expect anyone to take your columns seriously when you don&#8217;t even bother to read the manifesto that you label &#8220;lunatic.&#8221; Matthew, this is beneath you.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219841">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219841" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219841">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219841">James Masters</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219841" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219841" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>This is a well-argued article but I don’t think you have characterised the &#8216;spirit of the movement&#8217; correctly. I think you are talking about UKIP’s membership rather than the substantial numbers of new voters they are attracting. The two are not the same thing and the latter are more important: a party polling around the 25% mark has to be taken seriously. </p>
<p> UKIP&#8217;s new voters are expressing their opposition to LibLabCon. LibLabCon politicians may say different things from each other, but they speak in the same language and share the same underlying assumptions. People are voting for UKIP because they consider the language to be false and the assumptions to be wrong. Immigration is not the only example of this, but it is the single most important example. </p>
<p>On the subject of immigration, LibLabCon speak a language which is based on ideological obsessions, not reality. Certain facts about immigration are well-known in the real world but are completely off limits for those in the Westminster bubble and their cheerleaders in the media. Some groups of immigrants commit disproportionate levels of crime; some, in average/relative terms, consistently underachieve academically; other groups have, in general, integrated badly with the host population. Even if you ignore specific issues such as these, mass immigration has, unsurprisingly, been shown to worsen civic engagement and community relations in just about every measurable way.  </p>
<p>But you will never hear any recognition of this from LibLabCon, only about ‘vibrant diversity’ or ‘enrichment of the culture’ or some other such clichéd guff. Politicians who parrot out this sort of nonsense sound like what they are: phony and inauthentic. Farage does not sound phony or inauthentic. That is why his net approval rating is so high whereas MiliCam Clegg’s net approval ratings are all heavily in the red.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219851">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219851" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219851">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219851">Chris lancashire</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219851" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219851" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I think you&#8217;ve just proved your point Matthew.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219861">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219861" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219861">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219861">BobH2003</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219861" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219861" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Aw, poor hard done by Matthew Parris. Nobody likes him anymore. Somebody, other than his boyfriend, must have something nice to say about him!</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219871">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-219871" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-219871">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-219871">James Masters</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-219871" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-219871" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Another example of the mainstream getting it wrong is gay marriage. Hear me out.</p>
<p>Which of these two justifications for gay marriage do you prefer?</p>
<p>1) Allowing gay couples to get married won&#8217;t harm straight people. So if getting married would make a gay couple happy, they should be allowed to. Live and let live.</p>
<p>2) Homosexuality is just another version of heterosexuality. There are no qualitative differences between them. Anyone who disagrees is a bigot.</p>
<p>I suspect that most people who have not taken entrenched sides are far more likely to be persuaded by justification (1). However, we heard a whole lot more of (2) than we did of (1).</p>
<p>Bizarrely, peop
8000
le who give justification (2) describe themselves as &#8216;social liberals.&#8217; Ironically, the attitude underlying justification (2) has more similarities with the attitude of the churchmen who burned heretics at the stake a few centuries ago than it does with liberalism, on any reasonable definition of that term.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-219951">
