    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220481">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220481" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220481">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220481">Noel Matthews</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220481" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220481" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>It is pleasing for me that you say the Conservative party should have nothing to do with it. Most UKIP activists agree wholeheartedly. Those who join UKIP and campaign for us know exactly why they are doing so. We do not need the parties of Westminster to be more like us. They are yesterdays men and for our idea, the time has come.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220611">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220611" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220611">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220611">pjl20</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220611" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220611" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>As a UKIP party member and Branch Officer, I consider myself to be to be &#8216;middle of the road&#8217;, being neither to the right or the left of the political spectrum. The members who I know well, including the Regional Chair, are of similar outlook.</p>
<p>From where do these accusations of extremism come. From the fertile minds of journalists and opponents perhaps?</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
