    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220731">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220731" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220731">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220731">Colonel Mustard</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220731" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220731" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Not really very credible to complain of UKIP reference to EU &#8216;tyranny&#8217; as hyperbole and then label them as &#8216;extremists&#8217;. As with so much criticism of UKIP there is a startling lack of self-awareness.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220741">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220741" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220741">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220741">NotYouNotSure</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220741" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220741" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>&#8220;It distorts and simplifies the world&#8221;, funny coming from a somebody who distorts and simplifies the UKIP in this very article. The most important issue is obviously the EU, and it is not &#8220;smug and silly&#8221;. The question is simple, should the UK be sovereign or should the EU be sovereign, to dismiss this as a non issue or try obfuscate it as &#8220;its complicated&#8221; is probably what Matthew Parris intellectual forbears argued when they did not want to grant Indian independence and had not real way of defending British rule there. </p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220871">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220871" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220871">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220871">Bill_der_Berg</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220871" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220871" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>An important contributory factor to the rise of UKIP must be the belief that the established parties  lack the will and/or  the ability to tackle the &#8216;very real&#8217; problems that you identify.  I  do not think that the belief is unfounded.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220881">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220881" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220881">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220881">AlfTupperDarlin</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220881" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220881" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>UKIP &#8220;extremists&#8221; are the latest in a long line of &#8220;nutters&#8221; who trace their heritage and philosophy through Churchill, Henry VIII and Boudicca.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220891">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220891" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220891">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220891">shaworth</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220891" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220891" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>So it seems Matthew Parris is one of those Tories who likes to mock and insult the core vote. Well I hope you succeed in one of the things you call for in this article. If the right-wing elements are &#8216;repelled&#8217;, the Tory party will lose any hope of rekindling mass public appeal and can finally rot away. The slimy arrogance of people like you and Ken Clarke disgusts me, and under your ascendancy the party will get exactly what it deserves.</p>
<p>You forget that the place of the Tory party in British politics is not assured by divine right. If you insult your supporters long enough, if you liken them to extremists and claim they are ‘in need of psychiatric help&#8217;, they will desert you and the party will crumble.</p>
<p>UKIP’s incredible success represents something quite remarkable: a genuinely democratic shake-up of the political consensus, the first to take place for a very long time. It gives a voice to the disenchantment which has been felt for years in this country towards the left-leaning political class (of course if you are one of these people, i.e. one of the majority of people in this country, Matthew thinks you are, amongst other things, &#8216;paranoid&#8217;, ‘extreme’ and comparable to witch burners of the 17th century) .</p>
<p>Perhaps if he were more politically attuned, Matthew would seek to harness this force and steer it back to the mainstream, rather than let it flutter about on the fringes. Instead, he labels those involved as extremists, rules out any prospect of compromise and helps seal the imminent self-destruction of his party.</p>
<p>His desire to expel the &#8216;extreme&#8217; elements from the Tory party is actually quite funny. What he doesn&#8217;t realise is that the bulk of right-leaning people in this country would vote to oust him and his ilk from the Tory party, not the right-wing elements who he believes are wanting of &#8216;psychiatric help&#8217;.</p>
<p>Also, he waves away the idea of a ’liberal metropolitan elite’, likening it to a conspiracy theory. But this is just a weak attempt to dismiss the obvious. It’s not a matter of secret societies and shady backroom deals but a particular mindset which shows itself quite openly, whether in the courts or on Question Time, and which everyone apart from him can see. (Even Andrew Marr has testified to the “innate liberal bias” of the BBC.) By sneering at this, Matthew once again highlights the distance between himself and the core Tory voters. Thankfully the party he represents is not immortal; voters will only put up with these insults for so long before they take their custom elsewhere.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-220901">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220901" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220901">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220901">paulusdebierkabouter</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220901" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220901" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>M. Parris:<br />
&#8220;They are ordinary men and women who have become gripped by an ideology with a holistic world view.&#8221;<br />
&#8216;Holistic&#8217; is one of them fancy-dancy modern words, isn&#8217;t it?  If believing that countries (especially your own) should govern themselves, that they shouldn&#8217;t allow people to immigrate faster than they can integrate, and that direct democracy should replace representative democracy in as many circumstances as possible is what you describe as &#8216;holistic&#8217;, then you can sign me up as a holist.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="dsq-comment-220921">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-220921" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-220921">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-220921">terence patrick hewett</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-220921" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-220921" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>No one likes a smart-arse but Holism was coined in 1926 by Jan Smuts in his book, Holism and Evolution.  He defined it as &#8220;The tendency in nature to form wholes that are greater than the sum of the parts through creative evolution.&#8221;</p>
</div>
