    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="dsq-comment-229131">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-229131" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-229131">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-229131">Jonathan Kuperberg</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-229131" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-229131" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>They are not &#8220;ultra-&#8221; nationalist. Hence their rejection of the BNP. There are still several parts of their platform which raise red flags for me over how minorities would be treated when they took power, and some of their talk about liberal elites who enable scroungers can become Producerist boilerplate soaked in racist code if they start pushing certain buttons or develop it into a &#8220;conspiracy&#8221; narrative, but as far as UKIP now- judged by their manifesto, Farage statements, representative views of supporters and the majority of those Councillors they got elected once the few nuts are left out- there are significant differences between the &#8220;hard&#8221; right and the &#8220;far&#8221; right, which includes fascists among other ideologies based on a severe ethno-nationalism.and authoritarian state. </p>
<p>They are closer to Tea Party &#8220;God, gays and guns&#8221; Republicans except that few mention guns (unlike the BNP), and due to the low prevalence of hard-line Christian social conservatism here, they speak of God and the return of Christian values only vaguely and are only symbolically committed to heteronormativity, far from the sort of anti-gay stances and rhetoric that typify that brand of US politico/voter. There has not been much of the masculinist appeals to gender stereotype seen in the Far Right  either. They are also tolerant of diverse views on abortion, like all UK parties to the right of the Greens and (social) left of the Christian People&#8217;s Alliance. Militarism has never been their high point either&#8230; I agree UKIP have some worrying and possibly unworkable ideas but fascism is really overstating the case.</p>
<p>David Neiwert, an expert on this subject having covered bigots and extremists for 35 years, speaks of US right-wing ideology at the height of Bush II and fascism here, <a href="http://dneiwert.blogspot.co.uk/Rush%20Newspeak%20%20Fascism.pdf" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','download','http://dneiwert.blogspot.co.uk/Rush%20Newspeak%20%20Fascism.pdf']);" rel="nofollow">http://dneiwert.blogspot.co.uk/Rush%20Newspeak%20%20Fascism.pdf</a><br />
concluding they are not the same although further escalation of economic downturn and cultural hostility could turn a hard-right, &#8220;traditionalist&#8221; movement under most mature social systems into a variant of fascism.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
