            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-221341" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-221341" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>And you say you pondered your own article for a whole hour. Bless. How very, very patronising. You gave a second thought to whether you were right 
8000
and you decided, on reflection you were absolutely right. And as you say, there are an awful lot of lunatics in this country. People who cannot understand the unalloyed joy they should be experiencing under the benevolent government of the identikit Con/Lab/LibDem&#8217;s.<br />
You fall into the Left liberal role of mocking something that you accuse others of saying (or thinking) to generate a world that doesn&#8217;t exist. Maybe, just maybe the reason we don&#8217;t currently have a UKIP government is that too many of the &#8216;lunatics&#8217; actually don&#8217;t want the whole UKIP package, but do agree with the core of their ideas. We don&#8217;t want unfettered immigration, at least not while our idiotic, Left liberal welfare system is so attractive to so many. The lovely, Socialist France doesn&#8217;t allow it, so how did UKIP manage that, in a foreign country? It must be their fault, surely? No one else has such mad ideas? Except this very large proportion of the UK population. Is the EU the Soviet Union? Clearly not, we haven&#8217;t been fully subsumed yet. You can only be thankful that, whilst that is the goal (you can only argue if you believe no one can read EU documents), they are at least going about it peacefully and without the tanks. At present. And let us look at the current, biggest issue, the strangely titled &#8216;gay marriage&#8217;. There are two fundamentally important issues here. One is that the overwhelming majority of the people in this country (and many others it seems) are completely against this pointless, politically inspired agitation. They are being ignored. The second outrage is that no-one seems to want to mention that the issue of homosexual marriage is being forced on us (and those others) by more interference from an unaccountable body in &#8216;Europe&#8217;. UKIP is not the solution, there I can agree, but it is a sign of how far democracy in this country has been removed that it is the only near realistic option available to the people, people who are fed up of being lied to and misled whilst things are done in Brussels that we cannot control. So no, I don&#8217;t want to vote UKIP, but why would I vote for a Conservative party, my natural inclination, that is unrecognisable as such and indistinguishable from the Labour party. All of whom just carry on doing what they are told from abroad, whilst pretending that either the EU doesn&#8217;t exist or that they have some say in it. (Yes, one in 27).</p>
</div>
        </div>

