    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-221441">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-221441" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-221441">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-221441">walterellis</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-221441" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-221441" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Matthew: An excellent piece. I found exactly the same response from commenters when I wrote a blog over six months for the Telegraph. I support the EU, while believing it to be in urgent need of reform. The Faragistas who dominate readers&#8217; responses at the Telegraph rended me like dogs. It was never enough for me to point out that I shared many of their concerns, on the power of the Commission, on unfettered immigration, on the transfer of powers unnecessarily to Brussels. I was a<br />
 dupe of the evil tyrants in Europe whose chief goal was to humiliate Britain and reduce it to beggary. I was insulted at every turn. On one occasion, I was told that my dead father must have been a spineless coward to have raised a son like me. When I voluntarily gave up my blog, commenters crowed that I had been sacked and run out of town. It was, all in all, a disturbing, un-British experience – and made a mockery of the idea of free speech.</p>
<p>You are absolutely right in your argument. Most UKIP supporters are paranoid. We see this in the comments below by people who thought you intelligent until your raised your voice against their beloved movement. The good news is that they do not represent a majority of voters. Instead, they are a throwback to the attitudes of the 1930s, when Jews were blamed by an angry and frustrated minority for Britain&#8217;s ills and (ironically) there were calls for the UK to appease, and even make common cause, with the Fascist powers of Germany and Italy.</p>
<p>Britain faces a host of problems. So does France, so does America, so, even, does<br />
Germany (which requires a prosperous world into which to sell its goods). Immigration is a serious issue, as is militant Islam, as is the decline of British manufacturing, as is climate change. One can only laugh at the sabre-rattling of Cameron and Hague in relation to Syria when viewed against reports of how few soldiers we can afford, how few ships and how few aircraft.</p>
<p>Whatever problems exist, it is up to Britain, working with its friends and allies, to solve them – and I would include in that the need to redress the worsening imbalance between rich and poor, which is the source, ultimately, of so much<br />
discontent.</p>
<p>No country – not even Britain – is an island, not in the the 21st century. it is time we wakened up to the fact and faced our problems one-by-one. To blame everything on foreigners is to miss the point of the world in which, inescapably, we now live.</p>
</div>
        </div>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment even depth-2" id="dsq-comment-221471">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-221471" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-221471">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-221471">JustAnOtherRandomGit</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-221471" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-221471" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Oh, for goodness sake, I assumed that contributors on newspaper blogs had bullshit filters.  In the anonymity of a car, some drivers behave badly.  In the anonymity of internet comments, some people behave badly, it&#8217;s just human nature.</p>
<p>Your comment on UKIP voters is precisely wrong, though, I think you&#8217;ll find that many of the twenty-something % of the population who currently support them are mostly quite ordinary, even if internet commenters are not.  Personally, I am all in favour of European cooperation, so long as the EU institutions can be neutered in the style of the Holy Roman Emperors.  Fortunately, Merkel seems to be achieving this pretty well on her own, so there may be no need for me to vote UKIP.</p>
</div>
        </div>

