    <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="dsq-comment-221531">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-221531" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-221531">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-221531">Bill_der_Berg</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-221531" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-221531" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Matthew Parris has long taken a dim view of the plebs.  This came out very strongly in an article which he wrote for The Times some time ago. It is worth reading for his notions of how the public view certain important matters. My favourite is  &#8220;The idea in law, that a man is innocent until proved guilty, outrages them: why, after all, did the police arrest him in the first place?&#8221;  </p>
<p>No wonder Mr P concludes that  &#8220;The people are wrong. They probably<br />
always will be. It follows that in a democracy any responsible political leader<br />
must throughout his career spend much of his time and creative genius in<br />
finding sneaky ways to block the settled public will without becoming too<br />
unpopular for it.&#8221;.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.pubcurmudgeon.org.uk/misc/art_misguided.html" onclick="javascript:_gaq.push(['_trackEvent','outbound-comment','http://www.pubcurmudgeon.org.uk']);" rel="nofollow">http://www.pubcurmudgeon.org.uk/misc/art_misguided.html</a></p>
